**Abstract:**
Working notes on Aquinas's distinction between scitum (knowledge) and creditum (belief), dated December 31, 1992. The document critiques Aquinas's conception of faith as theoretical assent, arguing instead for faith as practical consent. It explores disagreements with Aquinas on revelation, biblical narrative, and the relationship between philosophy and theology, concluding that scholastic philosophy of religion is fundamentally misguided. Includes commentary on Motte's "Theodicee et theologie."

**AI Recommendation:** Core theoretical notes on faith vs. knowledge distinction; foundational for Chantilly project arguments.

